ladders.explanation:
This problem requires finding the minimum number of swaps needed to sort an array in ascending order. The selection sort approach provides a straightforward solution: we repeatedly find the smallest element in the unsorted portion of the array and swap it to its correct position, counting each swap. The intuition is that each element needs to be placed in its sorted position, and selection sort naturally identifies the correct element for each position through minimum finding. The algorithm works by maintaining two pointers: i for the current position being filled, and j for scanning the unsorted portion. For each i from 0 to n-2, we find the index of the minimum element in the subarray from i to n-1. If this minimum element is not already at position i, we swap it with the element at i and increment the swap counter. This ensures that after each iteration, the element at position i is in its final sorted position. The time complexity is O(n²) because for each of n positions, we potentially scan up to n elements to find the minimum. Space complexity is O(1) as we only use a few variables. This connects to the key subroutine (L1) which is the minimum finding operation. Common mistakes include not handling duplicate elements correctly (the algorithm works fine with duplicates), forgetting to count swaps when the minimum is already in place (shouldn't count), or off-by-one errors in loop boundaries. The algorithm is guaranteed to produce the minimum swaps for selection sort because each swap places an element in its final position, though note that this isn't necessarily the absolute minimum swaps possible across all algorithms—it's specifically for the selection sort approach.

Pseudocode:
function minSwapsSelectionSort(arr):
    n = length(arr)
    swaps = 0
    for i from 0 to n-2:
        min_idx = i
        for j from i+1 to n-1:
            if arr[j] < arr[min_idx]:
                min_idx = j
        if min_idx != i:
            swap(arr[i], arr[min_idx])
            swaps += 1
    return swaps

This sub-routine is the core operation in selection sort: given an array and a starting index, find the position of the minimum element in the subarray from that start to the end. The intuition is that to sort efficiently, we need to locate the element that belongs at the current position, and the minimum element in the unsorted portion is guaranteed to be that element. The algorithm initializes the minimum index to the start position, then iterates through the remaining elements, updating the minimum index whenever a smaller element is found. This linear scan ensures we correctly identify the smallest value. Time complexity is O(k) where k is the size of the subarray (worst-case O(n) when scanning nearly the entire array). Space complexity is O(1) as we only store the current minimum index. This feeds directly into L0 (full problem) by providing the element to swap into position. Common mistakes include starting the loop from the wrong index (should be start+1), not handling empty subarrays (ensure start < length), or comparing incorrectly (use < for minimum). This operation is fundamental to many sorting algorithms and selection-based problems.

