function findMinIndex(arr, start):
    min_idx = start
    for i from start+1 to length(arr)-1:
        if arr[i] < arr[min_idx]:
            min_idx = i
    return min_idx

This is the central technique of selection sort: we maintain a sorted portion at the beginning of the array and an unsorted portion after it. In each iteration, we find the minimum element in the unsorted portion and swap it with the first element of the unsorted portion (which becomes part of the sorted portion). The intuition is that by always picking the smallest available element, we build the sorted array from left to right in correct order. The algorithm uses two nested loops: the outer loop iterates through each position i from 0 to n-2 (since the last element will automatically be in place), and the inner loop finds the minimum in the subarray from i to n-1. If the minimum is not already at i, we swap. This ensures that after each outer iteration, the element at position i is in its final sorted position. Time complexity is O(n²) due to the nested loops, with exactly n(n-1)/2 comparisons in worst case. Space complexity is O(1). This connects to L1 (finding minimum) as the inner operation and L0 as the complete application. Common mistakes include swapping unnecessarily (check if min_idx != i first), incorrect loop ranges (outer to n-2, inner from i+1), or not updating the array in-place. This logic is a fundamental sorting strategy that emphasizes selection-based ordering.

